# Do you know simple statistics about the Olympic Games ?  
A simple data analysis using Wikipedia data.

![Olympic rings with transparent rims.svg](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Olympic_rings_with_transparent_rims.svg/1280px-Olympic_rings_with_transparent_rims.svg.png)

### Introduction  
The Olympic Games is an important international event featuring summer and winter sports. Summer Olympic Games and Winter Olympic Games are held every four years. 

The first games were in 776 BC. The first "modern" Olympics happened in 1896. In this analysis we will be interested for all Olympic Games from 1896 to 2018, including Summer Olympic Games, Winter Olympic Games, and a combined total of both.  

For this analysis, we are going to use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All-time_Olympic_Games_medal_table">this</a> Wikipedia data.

![An incomplete sphere made of large, white, jigsaw puzzle pieces. Each puzzle piece contains one glyph from a different writing system, with each glyph written in black.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Wikipedia-logo-v2.svg/800px-Wikipedia-logo-v2.svg.png)

So let's dive on.

## Part I : Which country has won the most gold medals in summer games ?

Let's begin with a simple question !

Obviously, this is the first question to come to mind when we speak about competitions : "Who had the most gold ?". And fortunately, with a simple manipulation we get it, and no surprise it's the USA !

## Part II : Which country had the biggest difference between their summer and winter gold medal counts ?

For now, let's make it a little bit harder !

In this part, we want to know the coutry that have the largest margin between summer gold medal and winter gold medal. Take a guess !

It's again the United States !!

## Part III : Which country has the biggest difference between their summer gold medal counts and winter gold medal counts relative to their total gold medal count ?

Let's take it to a high level of complexity !

For this part, let's try to answer the question of part 2 but relatively  to their total gold medal. 

Finally, it's not the USA. It's  Bulgaria.

## Part IV : Which are the top 5 countries if we weights each gold medal for 3 points, silver medals for 2 points, and bronze medals for 1 point ?

Now, let's answer a real difficult data analysis question !

We will try to find the Top 5 countries on collecting medals. But we can't give all medals the same value, no ?

For this purpose we will weighting medals  (gold medal for 3 pts, silver medals for 2 pts, and bronze medals for 1 pt)

The bar chart below shows that the United States have the first place (with a big difference), the second place was for the Soviet Union ! Great Britain, Germany and France were in the 3<sup>rd</sup>, 4<sup>th</sup>  and the 5<sup>th</sup> respectively (they were so close).

### Conclusion

In this article, we dived into the Olympic Games data on Wikipedia.

1.    We saw that the United States has won the most gold medals in summer games. In addition the USA had the biggest difference between their summer and winter gold medal counts.

2. The country that has the biggest difference between their summer gold medal counts and winter gold medal counts relative to their total gold medal count was Bulgaria.

3. Finally, the top 5 countries with weighted medals were the United States, the Soviet Union ,Great Britain, Germany and France in descending order.
